# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bellman-ford-algorithm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The **Bellman–Ford algorithm** is an algorithm that computes shortest paths from a single source vertex to all of the other vertices in a weighted digraph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] It is slower than Dijkstra's algorithm for the same problem, but more versatile, as it is capable of handling graphs in which some of the edge weights are negative numbers.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Alfonso Shimbel (1955), but is instead named after Richard Bellman and Lester Ford Jr., who published it in 1958 and 1956, respectively.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Moore also published a variation of the algorithm in 1959, and for this reason it is also sometimes called the **Bellman–Ford–Moore algorithm**.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Negative edge weights are found in various applications of graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a graph contains a "negative cycle" (i.e. a cycle whose edges sum to a negative value) that is reachable from the source, then there is no *cheapest* path: any path that has a point on the negative cycle can be made cheaper by one more walk around the negative cycle.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In such a case, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can detect and report the negative cycle.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Like Dijkstra's algorithm, Bellman–Ford proceeds by relaxation, in which approximations to the correct distance are replaced by better ones until they eventually reach the solution.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In both algorithms, the approximate distance to each vertex is always an overestimate of the true distance, and is replaced by the minimum of its old value and the length of a newly found path.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In each of these repetitions, the number of vertices with correctly calculated distances grows, from which it follows that eventually all vertices will have their correct distances.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] This method allows the Bellman–Ford algorithm to be applied to a wider class of inputs than Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The intermediate answers and the choices among equally short paths depend on the order of edges relaxed, but the final distances remain the same.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Bellman–Ford runs in $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ time, where $|V|$ and $|E|$ are the number of vertices and edges respectively.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Simply put, the algorithm initializes the distance to the source to 0 and all other nodes to infinity.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then for all edges, if the distance to the destination can be shortened by taking the edge, the distance is updated to the new lower value.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The core of the algorithm is a loop that scans across all edges at every loop.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Since the longest possible path without a cycle can be $|V|-1$ edges, the edges must be scanned $|V|-1$ times to ensure the shortest path has been found for all nodes.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] A final scan of all the edges is performed and if any distance is updated, then a path of length $|V|$ edges has been found which can only occur if at least one negative cycle exists in the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The edge (u, v) that is found in step 3 must be reachable from a negative cycle, but it isn't necessarily part of the cycle itself, which is why it's necessary to follow the path of predecessors backwards until a cycle is detected.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The above pseudo-code uses a Boolean array (`visited`) to find a vertex on the cycle, but any cycle finding algorithm can be used to find a vertex on the cycle.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] A common improvement when implementing the algorithm is to return early when an iteration of step 2 fails to relax any edges, which implies all shortest paths have been found, and therefore there are no negative cycles.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In that case, the complexity of the algorithm is reduced from $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ to $O(l\cdot |E|)$ where l is the maximum length of a shortest path in the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the inductive case, we first prove the first part.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Consider a moment when a vertex's distance is updated by `v.distance := u.distance + uv.weight`.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` is the length of some path from *source* to *u*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Then `u.distance + uv.weight` is the length of the path from *source* to *v* that follows the path from *source* to *u* and then goes to *v*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] For the second part, consider a shortest path *P* (there may be more than one) from *source* to *v* with at most *i* edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Let *u* be the last vertex before *v* on this path.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] By inductive assumption, `u.distance` after *i*−1 iterations is at most the length of this path from *source* to *u*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, `uv.weight + u.distance` is at most the length of *P*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In the *ith* iteration, `v.distance` gets compared with `uv.weight + u.distance`, and is set equal to it if `uv.weight + u.distance` is smaller.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Therefore, after *i* iterations, `v.distance` is at most the length of *P*, i.e., the length of the shortest path from *source* to *v* that uses at most *i* edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] If there are no negative-weight cycles, then every shortest path visits each vertex at most once, so at step 3 no further improvements can be made.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Conversely, suppose no improvement can be made.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] I.e., every cycle has nonnegative weight.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] When the algorithm is used to find shortest paths, the existence of negative cycles is a problem, preventing the algorithm from finding a correct answer.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] However, since it terminates upon finding a negative cycle, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used for applications in which this is the target to be sought – for example in cycle-cancelling techniques in network flow analysis.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] A distributed variant of the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used in distance-vector routing protocols, for example the Routing Information Protocol (RIP).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The algorithm is distributed because it involves a number of nodes (routers) within an Autonomous system (AS), a collection of IP networks typically owned by an ISP.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each node sends its table to all neighboring nodes.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] When a node receives distance tables from its neighbors, it calculates the shortest routes to all other nodes and updates its own table to reflect any changes.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] With this early termination condition, the main loop may in some cases use many fewer than |*V*| − 1 iterations, even though the worst case of the algorithm remains unchanged.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The following improvements all maintain the $O(|V|\cdot |E|)$ worst-case time complexity.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] A variation of the Bellman–Ford algorithm described by Moore (1959), reduces the number of relaxation steps that need to be performed within each iteration of the algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] If a vertex *v* has a distance value that has not changed since the last time the edges out of *v* were relaxed, then there is no need to relax the edges out of *v* a second time.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In this way, as the number of vertices with correct distance values grows, the number whose outgoing edges that need to be relaxed in each iteration shrinks, leading to a constant-factor savings in time for dense graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] This variation can be implemented by keeping a collection of vertices whose outgoing edges need to be relaxed, removing a vertex from this collection when its edges are relaxed, and adding to the collection any vertex whose distance value is changed by a relaxation step.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] In China, this algorithm was popularized by Fanding Duan, who rediscovered it in 1994, as the "shortest path faster algorithm".
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Yen (1970) described another improvement to the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] His improvement first assigns some arbitrary linear order on all vertices and then partitions the set of all edges into two subsets.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] The first subset, *Ef*, contains all edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* < *j*; the second, *Eb*, contains edges (*vi*, *vj*) such that *i* > *j*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is visited in the order *v1*, *v2*, ..., *v*|*V*|, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Ef*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each vertex is then visited in the order *v*|*V*|, *v*|*V*|−1, ..., *v*1, relaxing each outgoing edge from that vertex in *Eb*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Each iteration of the main loop of the algorithm, after the first one, adds at least two edges to the set of edges whose relaxed distances match the correct shortest path distances: one from *Ef* and one from *Eb*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] This modification reduces the worst-case number of iterations of the main loop of the algorithm from |*V*| − 1 to $|V|/2$ .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Another improvement, by Bannister & Eppstein (2012), replaces the arbitrary linear order of the vertices used in Yen's second improvement by a random permutation.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] This change makes the worst case for Yen's improvement (in which the edges of a shortest path strictly alternate between the two subsets *Ef* and *Eb*) very unlikely to happen.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] With a randomly permuted vertex ordering, the expected number of iterations needed in the main loop is at most $|V|/3$ .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Fineman (2024), at Georgetown University, created an improved algorithm that with high probability runs in ${\tilde {O}}(|V|^{8/9}\cdot |E|)$ time.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/bellman-ford-algorithm] Here, the ${\tilde {O}}$ is a variant of big O notation that hides logarithmic factors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] In mathematics, and more specifically in graph theory, a **directed graph** (or **digraph**) is a graph that is made up of a set of vertices connected by directed edges, often called **arcs**.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] It differs from an ordinary or undirected graph, in that the latter is defined in terms of unordered pairs of vertices, which are usually called *edges*, *links* or *lines*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The aforementioned definition does not allow a directed graph to have multiple arrows with the same source and target nodes, but some authors consider a broader definition that allows directed graphs to have such multiple arcs (namely, they allow the arc set to be a multiset).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] Sometimes these entities are called **directed multigraphs** (or **multidigraphs**).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] On the other hand, the aforementioned definition allows a directed graph to have loops (that is, arcs that directly connect nodes with themselves), but some authors consider a narrower definition that does not allow directed graphs to have loops.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] Directed graphs without loops may be called **simple directed graphs**, while directed graphs with loops may be called *loop-digraphs* (see section Types of directed graph).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] An arc (*x*, *y*) is considered to be directed *from* *x* *to* *y*; *y* is called the *head* and *x* is called the *tail* of the arc; *y* is said to be a *direct successor* of *x* and *x* is said to be a *direct predecessor* of *y*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] If a path leads from *x* to *y*, then *y* is said to be a *successor* of *x* and *reachable* from *x*, and *x* is said to be a *predecessor* of *y*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The arc (*y*, *x*) is called the *reversed arc* of (*x*, *y*).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a multidigraph with loops is the integer-valued matrix with rows and columns corresponding to the vertices, where a nondiagonal entry *a**ij* is the number of arcs from vertex *i* to vertex *j*, and the diagonal entry *a**ii* is the number of loops at vertex *i*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph is a logical matrix, and is unique up to permutation of rows and columns.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] Another matrix representation for a directed graph is its incidence matrix.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] For a vertex, the number of head ends adjacent to a vertex is called the *indegree* of the vertex and the number of tail ends adjacent to a vertex is its *outdegree* (called *branching factor* in trees).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The indegree of *v* is denoted deg−(*v*) and its outdegree is denoted deg+(*v*).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] A vertex with deg−(*v*) = 0 is called a *source*, as it is the origin of each of its outgoing arcs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] Similarly, a vertex with deg+(*v*) = 0 is called a *sink*, since it is the end of each of its incoming arcs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] If for every vertex *v* ∈ *V*, deg+(*v*) = deg−(*v*), the graph is called a *balanced directed graph*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The degree sequence of a directed graph is the list of its indegree and outdegree pairs; for the above example we have degree sequence ((2, 0), (2, 2), (0, 2), (1, 1)).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The degree sequence is a directed graph invariant so isomorphic directed graphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] However, the degree sequence does not, in general, uniquely identify a directed graph; in some cases, non-isomorphic digraphs have the same degree sequence.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The directed graph realization problem is the problem of finding a directed graph with the degree sequence a given sequence of positive integer pairs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] This problem can either be solved by the Kleitman–Wang algorithm or by the Fulkerson–Chen–Anstee theorem.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] A directed graph is *weakly connected* (or just *connected*) if the undirected *underlying graph* obtained by replacing all directed edges of the graph with undirected edges is a connected graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] A directed graph is *strongly connected* or *strong* if it contains a directed path from *x* to *y* (and from *y* to *x*) for every pair of vertices (*x*, *y*).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] The *strong components* are the maximal strongly connected subgraphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/directed-graph] A connected rooted graph (or *flow graph*) is one where there exists a directed path to every vertex from a distinguished *root vertex*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Second, the Bellman–Ford algorithm is used, starting from the new vertex q, to find for each vertex v the minimum weight *h*(*v*) of a path from q to v.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] If this step detects a negative cycle, the algorithm is terminated.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Next the edges of the original graph are reweighted using the values computed by the Bellman–Ford algorithm: an edge from u to v, having length ⁠ $w(u,v)$ ⁠, is given the new length *w*(*u*,*v*) + *h*(*u*) − *h*(*v*).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Finally, q is removed, and Dijkstra's algorithm is used to find the shortest paths from each node s to every other vertex in the reweighted graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The distance in the original graph is then computed for each distance D(u, v), by adding *h*(*v*) − *h*(*u*) to the distance returned by Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The first three stages of Johnson's algorithm are depicted in the illustration below.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The graph on the left of the illustration has two negative edges, but no negative cycles.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The center graph shows the new vertex q, a shortest path tree as computed by the Bellman–Ford algorithm with q as starting vertex, and the values *h*(*v*) computed at each other node as the length of the shortest path from q to that node.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Note that these values are all non-positive, because q has a length-zero edge to each vertex and the shortest path can be no longer than that edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] On the right is shown the reweighted graph, formed by replacing each edge weight ⁠ $w(u,v)$ ⁠ by *w*(*u*,*v*) + *h*(*u*) − *h*(*v*).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] In this reweighted graph, all edge weights are non-negative, but the shortest path between any two nodes uses the same sequence of edges as the shortest path between the same two nodes in the original graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The algorithm concludes by applying Dijkstra's algorithm to each of the four starting nodes in the reweighted graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] In the reweighted graph, all paths between a pair s and t of nodes have the same quantity *h*(*s*) − *h*(*t*) added to them.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The previous statement can be proven as follows: Let p be an ⁠ $s-t$ ⁠ path.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The bracketed expression is the weight of *p* in the original weighting.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Since the reweighting adds the same amount to the weight of every ⁠ $s-t$ ⁠ path, a path is a shortest path in the original weighting if and only if it is a shortest path after reweighting.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The weight of edges that belong to a shortest path from *q* to any node is zero, and therefore the lengths of the shortest paths from *q* to every node become zero in the reweighted graph; however, they still remain shortest paths.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Therefore, there can be no negative edges: if edge *uv* had a negative weight after the reweighting, then the zero-length path from *q* to *u* together with this edge would form a negative-length path from *q* to *v*, contradicting the fact that all vertices have zero distance from *q*.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The non-existence of negative edges ensures the optimality of the paths found by Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] The distances in the original graph may be calculated from the distances calculated by Dijkstra's algorithm in the reweighted graph by reversing the reweighting transformation.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/johnson-s-algorithm] Thus, when the graph is sparse, the total time can be faster than the Floyd–Warshall algorithm, which solves the same problem in time $O(|V|^{3})$ .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In graph theory, the **shortest path problem** is the problem of finding a path between two vertices (or nodes) in a graph such that the sum of the weights of its constituent edges is minimized.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The problem of finding the shortest path between two intersections on a road map may be modeled as a special case of the shortest path problem in graphs, where the vertices correspond to intersections and the edges correspond to road segments, each weighted by the length or distance of each segment.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The shortest path problem can be defined for graphs whether undirected, directed, or mixed.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The definition for undirected graphs states that every edge can be traversed in either direction.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Directed graphs require that consecutive vertices be connected by an appropriate directed edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Two vertices are adjacent when they are both incident to a common edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A path in an undirected graph is a sequence of vertices $P=(v_{1},v_{2},\ldots ,v_{n})\in V\times V\times \cdots \times V$ such that $v_{i}$ is adjacent to $v_{i+1}$ for $1\leq i<n$ .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Such a path P is called a path of length $n-1$ from $v_{1}$ to $v_{n}$ .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] These generalizations have significantly more efficient algorithms than the simplistic approach of running a single-pair shortest path algorithm on all relevant pairs of vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Several well-known algorithms exist for solving this problem and its variants.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Additional algorithms and associated evaluations may be found in Cherkassky, Goldberg & Radzik (1996).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] An algorithm using topological sorting can solve the single-source shortest path problem in time Θ(*E* + *V*) in arbitrarily-weighted directed acyclic graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The following table is taken from Schrijver (2004), with some corrections and additions.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A green background indicates an asymptotically best bound in the table; *L* is the maximum length (or weight) among all edges, assuming integer edge weights.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Finds a negative cycle or calculates distances to all vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The all-pairs shortest path problem finds the shortest paths between every pair of vertices v, v' in the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The all-pairs shortest paths problem for unweighted directed graphs was introduced by Shimbel (1953), who observed that it could be solved by a linear number of matrix multiplications that takes a total time of *O*(*V*4).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Shortest path algorithms are applied to automatically find directions between physical locations, such as driving directions on web mapping websites like MapQuest or Google Maps.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] For this application fast specialized algorithms are available.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] For example, if vertices represent the states of a puzzle like a Rubik's Cube and each directed edge corresponds to a single move or turn, shortest path algorithms can be used to find a solution that uses the minimum possible number of moves.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In a networking or telecommunications mindset, this shortest path problem is sometimes called the min-delay path problem and usually tied with a widest path problem.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] For example, the algorithm may seek the shortest (min-delay) widest path, or widest shortest (min-delay) path.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A more lighthearted application is the games of "six degrees of separation" that try to find the shortest path in graphs like movie stars appearing in the same film.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Other applications, often studied in operations research, include plant and facility layout, robotics, transportation, and VLSI design.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A road network can be considered as a graph with positive weights.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The nodes represent road junctions and each edge of the graph is associated with a road segment between two junctions.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The weight of an edge may correspond to the length of the associated road segment, the time needed to traverse the segment, or the cost of traversing the segment.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Using directed edges it is also possible to model one-way streets.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Such graphs are special in the sense that some edges are more important than others for long-distance travel (e.g. highways).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] This property has been formalized using the notion of highway dimension.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] There are a great number of algorithms that exploit this property and are therefore able to compute the shortest path a lot quicker than would be possible on general graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] All of these algorithms work in two phases.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In the first phase, the graph is preprocessed without knowing the source or target node.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In this phase, source and target node are known.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The idea is that the road network is static, so the preprocessing phase can be done once and used for a large number of queries on the same road network.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The algorithm with the fastest known query time is called hub labeling and is able to compute shortest path on the road networks of Europe or the US in a fraction of a microsecond.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] For shortest path problems in computational geometry, see Euclidean shortest path.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The shortest multiple disconnected path is a representation of the primitive path network within the framework of Reptation theory.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The widest path problem seeks a path so that the minimum label of any edge is as large as possible.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Other related problems may be classified into the following categories.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Unlike the shortest path problem, which can be solved in polynomial time in graphs without negative cycles, shortest path problems which include additional constraints on the desired solution path are called Constrained Shortest Path First, and are harder to solve.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] One example is the constrained shortest path problem, which attempts to minimize the total cost of the path while at the same time maintaining another metric below a given threshold.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] This makes the problem NP-complete (such problems are not believed to be efficiently solvable for large sets of data, see P = NP problem).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Another NP-complete example requires a specific set of vertices to be included in the path, which makes the problem similar to the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The TSP is the problem of finding the shortest path that goes through every vertex exactly once, and returns to the start.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The problem of finding the longest path in a graph is also NP-complete.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The Canadian traveller problem and the stochastic shortest path problem are generalizations where either the graph is not completely known to the mover, changes over time, or where actions (traversals) are probabilistic.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Sometimes, the edges in a graph have personalities: each edge has its own selfish interest.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] An example is a communication network, in which each edge is a computer that possibly belongs to a different person.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Different computers have different transmission speeds, so every edge in the network has a numeric weight equal to the number of milliseconds it takes to transmit a message.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Our goal is to send a message between two points in the network in the shortest time possible.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] If we know the transmission-time of each computer (the weight of each edge), then we can use a standard shortest-paths algorithm.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] If we do not know the transmission times, then we have to ask each computer to tell us its transmission-time.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] But, the computers may be selfish: a computer might tell us that its transmission time is very long, so that we will not bother it with our messages.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A possible solution to this problem is to use a variant of the VCG mechanism, which gives the computers an incentive to reveal their true weights.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In some cases, the main goal is not to find the shortest path, but only to detect if the graph contains a negative cycle.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Many problems can be framed as a form of the shortest path for some suitably substituted notions of addition along a path and taking the minimum.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The general approach to these is to consider the two operations to be those of a semiring.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Semiring multiplication is done along the path, and the addition is between paths.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] This general framework is known as the algebraic path problem.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] Most of the classic shortest-path algorithms (and new ones) can be formulated as solving linear systems over such algebraic structures.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] More recently, an even more general framework for solving these (and much less obviously related problems) has been developed under the banner of valuation algebras.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] In real-life, a transportation network is usually stochastic and time-dependent.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The travel duration on a road segment depends on many factors such as the amount of traffic (origin-destination matrix), road work, weather, accidents and vehicle breakdowns.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] A more realistic model of such a road network is a stochastic time-dependent (STD) network.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] There is no accepted definition of optimal path under uncertainty (that is, in stochastic road networks).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] It is a controversial subject, despite considerable progress during the past decade.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] One common definition is a path with the minimum expected travel time.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The main advantage of this approach is that it can make use of efficient shortest path algorithms for deterministic networks.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] However, the resulting optimal path may not be reliable, because this approach fails to address travel time variability.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] To tackle this issue, some researchers use travel duration distribution instead of its expected value.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] So, they find the probability distribution of total travel duration using different optimization methods such as dynamic programming and Dijkstra's algorithm .
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] These methods use stochastic optimization, specifically stochastic dynamic programming to find the shortest path in networks with probabilistic arc length.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The terms *travel time reliability* and *travel time variability* are used as opposites in the transportation research literature: the higher the variability, the lower the reliability of predictions.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] To account for variability, researchers have suggested two alternative definitions for an optimal path under uncertainty.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] The *most reliable path* is one that maximizes the probability of arriving on time given a travel time budget.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/negative-cycle] An *α-reliable path* is one that minimizes the travel time budget required to arrive on time with a given probability.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Graph theory is the study of graphs, systems of nodes or vertices connected in pairs by lines or edges.
