[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is an embedding of a graph onto a topological book, a space formed by joining a collection of half-planes along a shared line.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Usually, the vertices of the embedding are required to be on the line, which is called the spine of the embedding, and the edges of the embedding are required to lie within a single half-plane, one of the pages of the book.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a collection of mutually touching connected subgraphs, where two subgraphs touch if they share a vertex or each includes one endpoint of an edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The order of a bramble is the smallest size of a set of vertices that has a nonempty intersection with all of the subgraphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The treewidth of a graph is the maximum order of any of its brambles.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A path of degree-two vertices, ending at vertices whose degree is unequal to two.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , isthmus, or cut edge is an edge whose removal would disconnect the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A bridgeless graph is one that has no bridges; equivalently, a 2-edge-connected graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a cycle with at most one bridge; it must be a face boundary in any planar embedding of its graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A bridge of a cycle can also mean a path that connects two vertices of a cycle but is shorter than either of the paths in the cycle connecting the same two vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a graph in which every cycle of four or more vertices has a bridge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] has five vertices and six edges; it is formed by two triangles that share a vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , cactus tree, cactus, or Husimi tree is a connected graph in which each edge belongs to at most one cycle.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] If, in addition, each vertex belongs to at most two blocks, then it is called a Christmas cactus.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a regular graph with the smallest possible order for its girth.
