[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Canonical forms may also be called canonical invariants or complete invariants, and are sometimes defined only for the graphs within a particular family of graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is the process of computing a canonical form.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Carving width is a notion of graph width analogous to branchwidth, but using hierarchical clusterings of vertices instead of hierarchical clusterings of edges.
