[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The graph is Hamiltonian if and only if its circumference equals its order.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] of graphs or family of graphs is a (usually infinite) collection of graphs, often defined as the graphs having some specific property.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The word "class" is used rather than "set" because, unless special restrictions are made (such as restricting the vertices to be drawn from a particular set, and defining edges to be sets of two vertices) classes of graphs are usually not sets when formalized using set theory.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A color class of a colored graph is the set of vertices or edges having one particular color.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] , on edge coloring simple graphs, a graph is said to be of class one if its chromatic index equals its maximum degree, and class two if its chromatic index equals one plus the degree.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] According to Vizing's theorem, all simple graphs are either of class one or class two.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a graph that does not have an induced subgraph that is a claw.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a set of mutually adjacent vertices (or the complete subgraph induced by that set).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Sometimes a clique is defined as a maximal set of mutually adjacent vertices (or maximal complete subgraph), one that is not part of any larger such set (or subgraph).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] by operations that create a labeled vertex, form the disjoint union of two labeled graphs, add an edge connecting all pairs of vertices with given labels, or relabel all vertices with a given label.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A graph property is closed under some operation on graphs if, whenever the argument or arguments to the operation have the property, then so does the result.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For instance, hereditary properties are closed under induced subgraphs; monotone properties are closed under subgraphs; and minor-closed properties are closed under minors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] A closure of a directed graph is a set of vertices that have no outgoing edges to vertices outside the closure.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For instance, a sink is a one-vertex closure.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is the problem of finding a closure of minimum or maximum weight.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a coloring in which each vertex induces either an independent set (as in proper coloring) or a clique (as in a coloring of the complement).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] is a labeling of the vertices of a graph by elements from a given set of colors, or equivalently a partition of the vertices into subsets, called "color classes", each of which is associated with one of the colors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] Some authors use "coloring", without qualification, to mean a proper coloring, one that assigns different colors to the endpoints of each edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] can be colored with at most four colors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] It is so called because applying a greedy coloring algorithm to a degeneracy ordering of the graph uses at most this many colors.
