[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] The depth of a node in a rooted tree is the number of edges in the path from the root to the node.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For instance, the depth of the root is 0 and the depth of any one of its adjacent nodes is 1.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] That is, it is the maximum of the distances between pairs of vertices in the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] If the graph has weights on its edges, then its weighted diameter measures path length by the sum of the edge weights along a path, while the unweighted diameter measures path length by the number of edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p01] For disconnected graphs, definitions vary: the diameter may be defined as infinite, or as the largest diameter of a connected component, or it may be undefined.
