[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Information associated with a vertex or edge of a graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A labeled graph is a graph whose vertices or edges have labels.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] may be used to specify which objects of a graph have labels.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] refers to several different problems of assigning labels to graphs subject to certain constraints.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , in which the labels are interpreted as colors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , the vertices of a graph are said to be labeled if they are all distinguishable from each other.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] For instance, this can be made to be true by fixing a one-to-one correspondence between the vertices and the integers from 1 to the order of the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] When vertices are labeled, graphs that are isomorphic to each other (but with different vertex orderings) are counted as separate objects.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In contrast, when the vertices are unlabeled, graphs that are isomorphic to each other are not counted separately.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A leaf edge or pendant edge is the edge connecting a leaf vertex to its single neighbour.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] of a tree is a graph whose vertices are the leaves of the tree and whose edges connect leaves whose distance in the tree is at most a given threshold.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In an unweighted graph, the length of a cycle, path, or walk is the number of edges it uses.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In a weighted graph, it may instead be the sum of the weights of the edges that it uses.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A node's level in a rooted tree is the number of nodes in the path from the root to the node.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] For instance, the root has level 1 and any one of its adjacent nodes has level 2.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A set of all node having the same level or depth.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a computer representation of graphs for use in graph algorithms.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a variation of graph coloring in which each vertex has a list of available colors.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] For instance, a graph is locally finite if all of its neighborhoods are finite.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] or self-loop is an edge both of whose endpoints are the same vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a set of edges in which no two share any vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A vertex is matched or saturated if it is one of the endpoints of an edge in the matching.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] or complete matching is a matching that matches every vertex; it may also be called a 1-factor, and can only exist when the order is even.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A near-perfect matching, in a graph with odd order, is one that saturates all but one vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is the number of edges in a maximum matching.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a matching to which no additional edges can be added.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a complete subgraph that cannot be expanded to a larger complete subgraph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The word "maximal" should be distinguished from "maximum": a maximum subgraph is always maximal, but not necessarily vice versa.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A simple graph with a given property is maximal for that property if it is not possible to add any more edges to it (keeping the vertex set unchanged) while preserving both the simplicity of the graph and the property.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a planar graph such that adding any more edges to it would create a non-planar graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is maximum for a particular property if it is the largest subgraph (by order or size) among all subgraphs with that property.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is any of the largest cliques in a given graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph in which every three vertices have a unique median.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph in which every odd cycle of length five or more has at least two chords.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A subgraph of given graph is minimal for a particular property if it has that property but no proper subgraph of it also has the same property.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph that may include both directed and undirected edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , a graph in which each triple of vertices has at least one median vertex that belongs to shortest paths between all pairs of the triple.
