[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A multiple adjacency or multiple edge is a set of more than one edge that all have the same endpoints (in the same direction, in the case of directed graphs).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A graph with multiple edges is often called a multigraph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The multiplicity of an edge is the number of edges in a multiple adjacency.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The multiplicity of a graph is the maximum multiplicity of any of its edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is often used (especially in computer science) to denote the number of vertices in a given graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A vertex that is adjacent to a given vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] When the openness or closedness of a neighborhood is not specified, it is assumed to be open.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A graph in which attributes (e.g. names) are associated with the nodes and/or edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A non-edge or anti-edge is a pair of vertices that are not adjacent; the edges of the complement graph.
