[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] that every bridgeless cubic graph has a perfect matching.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A plane graph is a planar graph for which a particular embedding has already been fixed.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is an oriented tree; equivalently, a directed acyclic graph whose underlying undirected graph is a tree.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a closely related concept, derived from a power of a tree by taking the subgraph induced by the tree's leaves.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a method for analyzing complex networks by identifying cliques, bicliques, and stars within the network.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] are a phenomenon in which the number of vertices of a given degree is proportional to a power of the degree.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , a prime graph is a graph without any nontrivial modules.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , cuts whose cut-set is a complete bipartite graph, a prime graph is a graph without any splits.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Every quotient graph of a maximal decomposition by splits is a prime graph, a star, or a complete graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a connected graph that is not itself a product.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Every connected graph can be uniquely factored into a Cartesian product of prime graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A proper subgraph is a subgraph that removes at least one vertex or edge relative to the whole graph; for finite graphs, proper subgraphs are never isomorphic to the whole graph, but for infinite graphs they can be.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] or proper circular arc graph is an intersection graph of a collection of intervals or circular arcs (respectively) such that no interval or arc contains another interval or arc.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Proper interval graphs are also called unit interval graphs (because they can always be represented by unit intervals) or indifference graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is something that can be true of some graphs and false of others, and that depends only on the graph structure and not on incidental information such as labels.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Graph properties may equivalently be described in terms of classes of graphs (the graphs that have a given property).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] More generally, a graph property may also be a function of graphs that is again independent of incidental information, such as the size, order, or degree sequence of a graph; this more general definition of a property is also called an invariant of the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is an undirected graph in which each connected component has at most one cycle, or a directed graph in which each vertex has at most one outgoing edge.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A pseudograph is a graph or multigraph that allows self-loops.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A quasi-line graph or locally co-bipartite graph is a graph in which the open neighborhood of every vertex can be partitioned into two cliques.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] They are used in the structure theory of claw-free graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The edges of a quiver are called arrows.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph whose spectral expansion is as large as possible.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A ray, in an infinite graph, is an infinite simple path with exactly one endpoint.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] of a graph are equivalence classes of rays.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , a graph property is recognizable if its truth can be determined from the deck of the graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] Many graph properties are known to be recognizable.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] If the reconstruction conjecture is true, all graph properties are recognizable.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In this context, reconstruction is the formation of a graph from its deck.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A simple cycle consisting of exactly four edges and four vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A regular tournament is a tournament where in-degree equals out-degree for all vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a form of logic in which variables may represent vertices, edges, sets of vertices, and (sometimes) sets of edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] This logic includes predicates for testing whether a vertex and edge are incident, as well as whether a vertex or edge belongs to a set.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] To be distinguished from first order logic, in which variables can only represent vertices.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph without loops and without multiple adjacencies.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] That is, each edge connects two distinct endpoints and no two edges have the same endpoints.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A simple edge is an edge that is not part of a multiple adjacency.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In many cases, graphs are assumed to be simple unless specified otherwise.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A simple path or a simple cycle is a path or cycle that has no repeated vertices and consequently no repeated edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A sink, in a directed graph, is a vertex with no outgoing edges (out-degree equals 0).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph in which most nodes are not neighbors of one another, but most nodes can be reached from every other node by a small number of hops or steps.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a simple, connected, bridgeless cubic graph with chromatic index equal to 4.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A source, in a directed graph, is a vertex with no incoming edges (in-degree equals 0).
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a subspace of the edge space that has the cut-sets of the graph as its elements.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] has the Eulerian spanning subgraphs as its elements.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A spanner is a (usually sparse) graph whose shortest path distances approximate those in a dense graph or other metric space.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] , spanning trees of a graph whose distances approximate the graph distances, and graph spanners, sparse subgraphs of a dense graph whose distances approximate the original graph's distances.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A greedy spanner is a graph spanner constructed by a greedy algorithm, generally one that considers all edges from shortest to longest and keeps the ones that are needed to preserve the distance approximation.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A subgraph is spanning when it includes all of the vertices of the given graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] (spanning subgraphs that are matchings).
