[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] In some definitions the same property should also be true for all subgraphs of the given graph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is the branch of graph theory that uses spectra to analyze graphs.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a graph whose vertices can be partitioned into a clique and an independent set.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A related class of graphs, the double split graphs, are used in the proof of the strong perfect graph theorem.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] of an arbitrary graph is a partition of its vertices into two nonempty subsets, such that the edges spanning this cut form a complete bipartite subgraph.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A split is called a strong split when it is not crossed by any other split.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A split is called nontrivial when both of its sides have more than one vertex.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A graph is called prime when it has no nontrivial splits.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] (sometimes called vertex cleaving) is an elementary graph operation that splits a vertex into two, where these two new vertices are adjacent to the vertices that the original vertex was adjacent to.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The inverse of vertex splitting is vertex contraction.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] of a bipartite graph is the subgraph of its square induced by one side of the bipartition.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a planar graph that can be drawn so that all bounded faces are 4-cycles and all vertices of degree ≤ 3 belong to the outer face.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] defined from points in the plane with integer coordinates connected by unit-length edges.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] The special case of a star with three leaves is called a claw.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is the minimum ratio of the number of edges removed from the graph to components created, over all possible removals; it is analogous to toughness, based on vertex removals.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a regular graph in which every two adjacent vertices have the same number of shared neighbours and every two non-adjacent vertices have the same number of shared neighbours.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] is a chordal graph in which every even cycle of length six or more has an odd chord.
[src:bellman-ford-algorithm/weighted-graph-p02] A strongly perfect graph is a graph in which every induced subgraph has an independent set meeting all maximal cliques.
